 Register of Historic Places listings in DeKalb County, Illinois]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book|first=Richard L. (editor)|last=Forstall|year=1996|title=Population of states and counties of the United States: 1790 to 1990 : from the twenty-one decennial censuses|publisher=US Department of Commerce, Bureau of the Census, Population Division|isbn=0-934213-48-8}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070310144543/http://www.cyberdriveillinois.com/departments/archives/irad/edgar.html US Census Bureau 2007 TIGER/Line Shapefiles]\n* {{GNIS|422190|DeKalb County, Illinois}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081205020547/http://www.nationalatlas.gov/ US National Atlas]\n\n==Further reading==\n* Eric W. Mogren. ''Native Soil: A History of the DeKalb County Farm Bureau'' (DeKalb: [[Northern Illinois University Press]], 2005), 288 pp.\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://dekalbcounty.org/}}\n* [http://history.rays-place.com/il/cty-dekalb.htm History pages for DeKalb County towns and cities]{{dead link|date=April 2020|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}\n* {{curlie|Regional/North_America/Illinois/Counties/DeKalb|De Kalb County}}\n* [http://www.dcysb.com DeKalb County Youth Service Bureau]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20020607234409/http://dig.lib.niu.edu/dekalb/index.html Taming the Wild Prairie: A History of DeKalb County, Illinois, 1837-1900, Illinois Historical Digitization Projects at Northern Illinois University Libraries]\n* [http://www.DeKalbCountyOnline.com DeKalb County Online Newspaper]\n\n{{Geographic location\n|Centre    = DeKalb County, Illinois\n|North     = [[Boone County, Illinois|Boone County]]\n|Northeast = [[McHenry County, Illinois|McHenry County]]\n|East      = [[Kane County, Illinois|Kane County]]\n|Southeast = [[Kendall County, Illinois|Kendall County]]\n|South     = [[LaSalle County, Illinois|LaSalle County]]\n|West      = [[Lee County, Illinois|Lee County]] and [[Ogle County, Illinois|Ogle County]]\n|Northwest = [[Winnebago County, Illinois|Winnebago County]]\n}}\n{{DeKalb County, Illinois}}\n{{Chicagoland}}\n{{Illinois}}\n{{coord|41|53|37|N|88|46|13|W|display=title|type:adm2nd_region:US-IL_source:GNIS}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dekalb County, Illinois}}\n[[Category:DeKalb County, Illinois| ]]\n[[Category:1837 establishments in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Chicago metropolitan area]]\n[[Category:Illinois counties]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1837]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|County in Illinois}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox U.S. county\n |county           = DeKalb County\n |state            = Illinois\n |seal             = DeKalb County il seal.png\n |founded          = 4 March 1837\n |founded date     = March 4\n |seat wl          = Sycamore\n| largest city wl  = DeKalb\n |area_total_sq_mi = 635\n |area_land_sq_mi  = 631\n |area_water_sq_mi = 3.4\n |area percentage  = 0.5\n |population_as_of = 2010\n |population_total = 105160\n |pop_est_as_of    = 2018\n |population_est   = 104143\n |population_density_sq_mi = auto\n |web              = www.dekalbcounty.org\n |time zone        = Central\n |named for        = [[Johann de Kalb]]\n |ex image         = DeKalb County Courthouse2.jpg\n |ex image cap     = DeKalb County's Court House\n| district         = 14th\n| district2        = 16th\n}}\n'''DeKalb County''' is a [[County (United States)|county]] located in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Illinois]]. As of the [[2010 United States Census]], the population was 105,160.<ref name=QF>{{cite web|title=State & County QuickFacts|url=http://quickfacts.census.gov/qfd/states/17/17037.html|publisher=US Census Bureau|accessdate=July 4, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606162112/http://quickfacts.census.gov/qfd/states/17/17037.html|archivedate=June 6, 2011}}</ref> Its [[county seat]] is [[Sycamore, Illinois|Sycamore]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx |accessdate=7 June 2011|title=Find a County|publisher=National Association of Counties|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110531210815/http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx|archivedate=31 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nDeKalb County is part of the [[Chicago]]-[[Naperville, Illinois|Naperville]]-[[Elgin, Illinois|Elgin]], IL-[[Indiana|IN]]-[[Wisconsin|WI]] [[Chicago metropolitan area|Metropolitan Statistical Area]].\n\n==History==\nDeKalb County was formed on 4 March 1837,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ilsos.gov/isa/localgovnameindexsrch.jsp|title=Name Index to Illinois Local Governments|author=Illinois Regional Archives Depository System|work=Illinois State Archives|publisher=[[Illinois Secretary of State]]|accessdate=30 August 2013}}</ref> out of [[Kane County, Illinois]]. The County was named for [[Johann de Kalb]],<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_9V1IAAAAMAAJ|title=The Origin of Certain Place Names in the United States|publisher=Govt. Print. Off.|author=Gannett, Henry|year=1905|page=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_9V1IAAAAMAAJ/page/n102 103]}}</ref> a German ([[Bavaria]]n) hero of the [[American Revolutionary War]]. DeKalb County's area is approximately 632.7 square miles, located 63 miles west of Chicago. There are 19 townships in the county with the county seat at Sycamore.\n\nBetween 1834 and 1837, white men began to settle in DeKalb County along the streams and wooded areas because of the fertile soil, wild game, and food and water opportunities. Major growth stemmed from the introduction of the railroad which brought easier methods of transportation and opportunities for industrial growth. Early industries based in DeKalb County included Sandwich Mfg. Co, Marsh Harvester Co, [[barbed wire]], and [[George H. Gurler|Gurler Bros Pure Milk Co]].\n\nThe county is noted for agriculture. In 1852, the DeKalb Agricultural Society produced the county's first Agricultural Fair, in Sycamore. Eventually farmers, businessmen, bankers and newspapermen organized to become the DeKalb County Soil Improvement Association, which later was split into DeKalb County Farm Bureau and DeKalb Agricultural Association ([[DeKalb Genetics Corporation|DEKALB AgResearch, Inc.]], Monsanto). DeKalb County is credited with being the birthplace of the Farm Bureau movement. DeKalb County is also the 2nd largest hog producing county in Illinois and the 66th largest in the nation.\n\nEducation has played an important role in the area with [[Northern Illinois University]] located in [[DeKalb, Illinois|DeKalb]] and [[Kishwaukee College]] located in [[Malta, Illinois|Malta]]. A major fair has been held each year since 1887 at the [[Sandwich, Illinois#Sanwich fair|Sandwich Fairgrounds]] in Sandwich.\n<gallery>File:DeKalb  County Illinois 1837.png|DeKalb County at  the time  of its creation in 1837</gallery>\n\n==Pronunciation==\nUnlike similarly spelled locations, such as [[DeKalb County, Georgia]], DeKalb denizens from Illinois pronounce the county name {{IPAc-en|d|\u1d7b|\u02c8|k|\u00e6|l|b}} {{respell|di|KALB|'}}, with an L sound, as in German.\n\n==Geography==\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau|US Census Bureau]], the county has a total area of {{convert|635|sqmi}}, of which {{convert|631|sqmi}} is land and {{convert|3.4|sqmi}} (0.5%) is water.<ref name=CD/>\n\n===Climate and weather===\n{{climate chart\n|[[Sycamore, Illinois]]\n|10|27|1.54\n|16|32|1.40\n|26|44|2.46\n|37|58|3.52\n|48|70|4.21\n|58|80|4.49\n|63|84|4.22\n|61|81|4.48\n|51|74|3.51\n|40|62|2.60\n|28|45|2.82\n|17|32|2.13\n|float=right\n|units=imperial\n|clear=both\n|source=The Weather Channel<ref name=WX>{{cite web|url=http://www.weather.com/weather/wxclimatology/monthly/graph/USIL1144|title=Monthly Averages for Sycamore IL|accessdate=27 January 2011|publisher=The Weather Channel}}</ref>}}\nIn recent years, average temperatures in the county seat of Sycamore have ranged from a low of {{convert|10|\u00b0F}} in January to a high of {{convert|84|\u00b0F}} in July, although a record low of {{convert|-27|\u00b0F}} was recorded in January 1985 and a record high of {{convert|103|\u00b0F}} was recorded in August 1988.  Average monthly precipitation ranged from {{convert|1.40|in}} in February to {{convert|4.49|in}} in June.<ref name=WX/>\n\n===Adjacent counties===\n{{div col}}\n*[[Boone County, Illinois|Boone County]] - north\n*[[McHenry County, Illinois|McHenry County]] - northeast\n*[[Kane County, Illinois|Kane County]] - east\n*[[Kendall County, Illinois|Kendall County]] - southeast\n*[[LaSalle County, Illinois|LaSalle County]] - south\n*[[Lee County, Illinois|Lee County]] - west\n*[[Ogle County, Illinois|Ogle County]] - west\n*[[Winnebago County, Illinois|Winnebago County]] - northwest\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Major highways===\n{{div col}}\n* [[File:I-88.svg|25px]] [[Interstate 88 (west)|Interstate 88]]\n* [[File:US 30.svg|25px]] [[US Route 30]]\n* [[File:US 34.svg|25px]] [[US Route 34]]\n* [[File:Illinois 23.svg|25px]] [[Illinois Route 23]]\n* [[File:Illinois 38.svg|25px]] [[Illinois Route 38]]\n* [[File:Illinois 64.svg|25px]] [[Illinois Route 64]]\n* [[File:Illinois 72.svg|25px]] [[Illinois Route 72]]\n* [[File:Illinois 110.svg|25px]] [[Illinois Route 110]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1840= 1697\n|1850= 7540\n|1860= 19086\n|1870= 23265\n|1880= 26768\n|1890= 27066\n|1900= 31756\n|1910= 33457\n|1920= 31339\n|1930= 32644\n|1940= 34388\n|1950= 40781\n|1960= 51714\n|1970= 71654\n|1980= 74624\n|1990= 77932\n|2000= 88969\n|2010= 105160\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=104143\n|estref=<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=November 6, 2019}}</ref>\n|align-fn=center\n|footnote=US Decennial Census<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census.html|title=US Decennial Census|publisher=US Census Bureau|accessdate=July 4, 2014}}</ref><br>1790-1960<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mapserver.lib.virginia.edu|title=Historical Census Browser|publisher=University of Virginia Library|accessdate=July 4, 2014}}</ref> 1900-1990<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/population/cencounts/il190090.txt|title=Population of Counties by Decennial Census: 1900 to 1990|publisher=US Census Bureau|accessdate=July 4, 2014}}</ref><br>1990-2000<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/population/www/cen2000/briefs/phc-t4/tables/tab02.pdf|title=Census 2000 PHC-T-4. Ranking Tables for Counties: 1990 and 2000|publisher=US Census Bureau|accessdate=July 4, 2014}}</ref> 2010-2013<ref name=QF/>\n}}\n{{Stack|[[File:USA DeKalb County, Illinois age pyramid.svg|thumb|left|2000 census age pyramid for DeKalb County with a marked spike in college-aged individuals due to Northern Illinois University]]}}\n\nAs of the [[2010 United States Census]], there were 105,160&nbsp;people, 38,484&nbsp;households, and 23,781&nbsp;families residing in the county.<ref name=DP1>{{cite web|url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_DP/DPDP1/0500000US17037|title=Profile of General Population and Housing Characteristics: 2010 Demographic Profile Data|accessdate=11 July 2015|publisher=US Census Bureau|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213033826/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_DP/DPDP1/0500000US17037|archive-date=February 13, 2020|url-status=dead}}</ref> The population density was {{convert|166.6|PD/sqmi}}. There were 41,079 housing units at an average density of {{convert|65.1|/sqmi}}.<ref name=CD>{{cite web|url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/GCTPH1.CY10/0500000US17037|accessdate=11 July 2015|title=Population, Housing Units, Area, and Density: 2010 - County|publisher=US Census Bureau|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200212201456/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/GCTPH1.CY10/0500000US17037|archive-date=February 12, 2020|url-status=dead}}</ref> The racial makeup of the county was 85.1% white, 6.4% black or African American, 2.3% Asian, 0.3% American Indian, 3.9% from other races, and 2.0% from two or more races. Those of Hispanic or Latino origin made up 10.1% of the population.<ref name=DP1/> In terms of ancestry, 32.6% were [[Germans|German]], 17.5% were [[Irish people|Irish]], 8.7% were [[English people|English]], 7.0% were [[Poles|Polish]], 6.4% were [[Italians|Italian]], 6.3% were [[Swedes|Swedish]], and 3.8% were [[Americans|American]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/10_5YR/DP02/0500000US17037|title=Selected Social Characteristics in the United States \u2013 2006-2010 American Community Survey 5-Year Estimates|accessdate=11 July 2015|publisher=US Census Bureau|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213023844/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/10_5YR/DP02/0500000US17037|archive-date=February 13, 2020|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOf the 38,484&nbsp;households, 31.9% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 47.2% were married couples living together, 10.2% had a female householder with no husband present, 38.2% were non-families, and 25.8% of all households were made up of individuals. The average household size was 2.56 and the average family size was 3.11. The median age was 29.3 years.<ref name=DP1/>\n\nThe median income for a household in the county was $54,002 and the median income for a family was $70,713. Males had a median income of $50,192 versus $35,246 for females. The per capita income for the county was $24,179. About 7.7% of families and 14.6% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 13.2% of those under age 18 and 4.5% of those age 65 or over.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/10_5YR/DP03/0500000US17037|title=Selected Economic Characteristics \u2013 2006-2010 American Community Survey 5-Year Estimates|accessdate=11 July 2015|publisher=US Census Bureau|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213020922/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/10_5YR/DP03/0500000US17037|archive-date=February 13, 2020|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Communities==\n===Cities===\n{{div col}}\n*[[DeKalb, Illinois|DeKalb]]\n*[[Genoa, Illinois|Genoa]]\n*[[Sandwich, Illinois|Sandwich]] (mostly)\n*[[Sycamore, Illinois|Sycamore]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Town===\n*[[Cortland, Illinois|Cortland]]\n\n===Villages===\n{{div col|colwidth=15em}}\n* [[Hinckley, Illinois|Hinckley]]\n* [[Kingston, Illinois|Kingston]]\n* [[Kirkland, Illinois|Kirkland]]\n* [[Lee, Illinois|Lee]] (part)\n* [[Malta, Illinois|Malta]]\n* [[Maple Park, Illinois|Maple Park]] (part)\n* [[Shabbona, Illinois|Shabbona]]\n* [[Somonauk, Illinois|Somonauk]] (mostly)\n* [[Waterman, Illinois|Waterman]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Unincorporated Communities===\n{{div col|colwidth=15em}}\n* [[Afton Center, Illinois|Afton Center]]\n* [[Charter Grove, Illinois|Charter Grove]]\n* [[Clare, Illinois|Clare]]\n* [[Colvin Park, Illinois|Colvin Park]]\n* [[Elva, Illinois|Elva]]\n* [[Esmond, Illinois|Esmond]]\n* [[Fairdale, Illinois|Fairdale]]\n* [[Mayfield Township, DeKalb County, Illinois#Unincorporated towns|Five Points]]\n* [[Franks, Illinois|Franks]]\n* [[McGirr, Illinois|McGirr]]\n* [[New Lebanon, Illinois|New Lebanon]]\n* [[Rollo, Illinois|Rollo]]\n* [[Wilkinson, Illinois|Wilkinson]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Townships===\n{{div col|colwidth=15em}}\n* [[Afton Township, DeKalb County, Illinois|Afton]]\n* [[Clinton Township, DeKalb County, Illinois|Clinton]]\n* [[Cortland Township, DeKalb County, Illinois|Cortland]]\n* [[DeKalb Township, DeKalb County, Illinois|DeKalb]]\n* [[Franklin Township, DeKalb County, Illinois|Franklin]]\n* [[Genoa Township, DeKalb County, Illinois|Genoa]]\n* [[Kingston Township, DeKalb County, Illinois|Kingston]]\n* [[Malta Township, DeKalb County, Illinois|Malta]]\n* [[Mayfield Township, DeKalb County, Illinois|Mayfield]]\n* [[Milan Township, DeKalb County, Illinois|Milan]]\n* [[Paw Paw Township, DeKalb County, Illinois|Paw Paw]]\n* [[Pierce Township, DeKalb County, Illinois|Pierce]]\n* [[Sandwich Township, DeKalb County, Illinois|Sandwich]]\n* [[Shabbona Township, DeKalb County, Illinois|Shabbona]]\n* [[Somonauk Township, DeKalb County, Illinois|Somonauk]]\n* [[South Grove Township, DeKalb County, Illinois|South Grove]]\n* [[Squaw Grove Township, DeKalb County, Illinois|Squaw Grove]]\n* [[Sycamore Township, DeKalb County, Illinois|Sycamore]]\n* [[Victor Township, DeKalb County, Illinois|Victor]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Politics==\nAs part of [[Northern Illinois]], DeKalb County was a stronghold for the [[Free Soil Party]] in its early elections \u2013 being among nine Illinois counties to support [[Martin Van Buren]] in 1848 \u2013 and became overwhelmingly Republican for the century following that party's formation. The only time it did not back the official GOP nominee between 1856 and 1988 was in 1912 when the Republican Party was mortally divided and [[Progressive Party (United States, 1912)|Progressive]] [[Theodore Roosevelt]] won almost half the county's vote. Republican candidate [[Alf Landon]], who lost 46 of 48 states in 1936, won DeKalb County by double digits, whilst even [[Barry Goldwater]] \u2013 renowned for his antagonism towards the establishment \u2013 won by seven percent despite losing sixteen percent of the vote compared to [[Richard Nixon]] in 1960.\n\nAround the turn of the twenty first century, DeKalb County shifted more toward a balance of power in national elections, owing to the growth of the largely Democrat student population in DeKalb.  DeKalb County still remains solidly Republican for most local elected officials, however, with all municipalities outside of the city of [[DeKalb, Illinois|DeKalb]] voting strongly [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]].\n\nIn 1992, with the third party entrance of [[Ross Perot]] siphoning votes from Republican [[George H.W. Bush]], [[Bill Clinton]] became the first Democrat to carry the county in 140 years, and in 2008 Illinois son, [[Barack Obama]], became the first Democrat to win an absolute majority since Van Buren in the county's first-ever Presidential election of 1840. Obama repeated this in 2012, but economic concerns in the rust belt caused a sizeable swing away from [[Hillary Clinton]] in 2016, although she still narrowly won the county.\n\n{{Hidden begin\n|titlestyle = background:#ccccff;\n|title      = Presidential election results\n}}\n{| align=\"center\" border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"float:right; margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|+ '''Presidential election results'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uselectionatlas.org/RESULTS|title=Atlas of US Presidential Elections|last=Leip|first=David|website=uselectionatlas.org|access-date=1 November 2018}}</ref>\n|- bgcolor=lightgrey\n! Year\n! [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n! [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n! [[Third Party (United States)|Third parties]]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[United States presidential election in Illinois, 2016|2016]]'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|43.8% ''19,091''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''46.9%''' ''20,466''\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|9.3% ''4,043''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[United States presidential election in Illinois, 2012|2012]]'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|45.9% ''18,934''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''51.4%''' ''21,207''\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|2.7% ''1,100''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[United States presidential election in Illinois, 2008|2008]]'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|40.6% ''18,266''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shad